Below is a **complete, self‑contained example** that shows one idiomatic way to expose a C++ iterator from *libpcapng* to OCaml.  
It contains

* the **public OCaml interface** (`pcapng.mli`);
* the **C‑stub implementation** (`pcapng_stubs.c` – compiled as C++ with `extern "C"` entry points);
* a tiny **Makefile fragment** that shows how to build the stub and generate the OCaml library.

The design tries to keep the OCaml side as simple as possible while still giving the user the freedom to:

1. **Iterate with a callback** – the most natural way for OCaml code (`Pcapng.iter`);
2. **Pull frames manually** (`Pcapng.next`) – useful when you need more control (e.g. early exit, selective processing);
3. **Inspect a frame** (`timestamp`, `data`, …) – the frame is an abstract OCaml value that owns a C++ `Frame*` and is automatically freed by the GC.

---

## 1. OCaml public interface – `pcapng.mli`

```ocaml
(* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   pcapng.mli  –  OCaml bindings for libpcapng (C++ iterator)
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- *)

(** {1 Overview}

    The library works with *pcapng* files that contain a sequence of
    frames.  Internally the C++ library exposes a class

    ```cpp
    class Pcapng {
      public:
        class iterator { … };
        iterator begin() const;
        iterator end()   const;
    };
    ```

    The binding wraps the iterator in an opaque OCaml value of type
    [`t`].  The user can either walk the whole file with a callback
    (`iter`) or fetch frames one‑by‑one (`next`).  Each frame is
    represented by an abstract value of type [`frame`]; accessor
    functions are provided to read its fields.

    The binding takes care of memory management: both iterators and
    frames are allocated on the C++ heap and are released automatically
    when the corresponding OCaml values are collected (via a custom
    block finaliser).
*)

(** The opaque type that represents a *pcapng* file iterator. *)
type t

(** The opaque type that represents a single frame.  The value is
    immutable – you can only read information from it. *)
type frame

(** Open a pcapng file and obtain an iterator.  Raises [Invalid_argument]
    if the file cannot be opened or is not a valid pcapng file. *)
val open_file : string -> t

(** Close the iterator and free the underlying C++ object.  After calling
    this function the iterator must no longer be used.  The call is
    idempotent – calling it twice is a no‑op. *)
val close : t -> unit

(** {2 Frame accessors} *)

(** Return the raw packet payload as a [bytes] value. *)
val data : frame -> bytes

(** Return the packet timestamp (nanoseconds since the Unix epoch) as an
    [int64]. *)
val timestamp : frame -> int64

(** Return the original length of the packet (as reported by the capture
    file). *)
val orig_len : frame -> int

(** {2 Iteration primitives} *)

(** Walk the whole file, invoking the supplied OCaml function on each frame.
    The callback receives a *fresh* [`frame`] value that is owned by the
    iterator (i.e. it will be freed automatically when the iterator is
    closed or GC‑collected).  If the callback raises an exception, iteration
    stops and the exception propagates to the caller.

    The function is deliberately *tail‑recursive* on the C side – no OCaml
    stack is built.  This makes it safe even for very large captures. *)
val iter : t -> (frame -> unit) -> unit

(** Pull the next frame from the iterator, if any.  Returns [None] when the
    iterator has reached the end of the file.  The returned [`frame`] is a
    fresh value that the caller owns; it must be kept alive (e.g. by
    binding it to a variable) until it is no longer needed – the GC will
    free it automatically. *)
val next : t -> frame option
```

